Label: Physiologically Based Pharmacokinetic Modeling
Defination: Physiologically based pharmacokinetic (PBPK) modeling is a mathematical modeling technique that predicts the absorption, distribution, metabolism, and excretion (ADME) of synthetic or natural chemical substances in humans and other animal species
Textual Defination: Physiologically based pharmacokinetic (PBPK) modeling is a mathematical modeling technique that predicts the absorption, distribution, metabolism, and excretion (ADME) of synthetic or natural chemical substances in humans and other animal species

Label: Whole body PBPK Model
Defination: A whole-body PBPK model contains an explicit representation of the organs that are most relevant to the absorption, distribution, excretion, and metabolization of the drug/chemicals due to their physiological/pharmacological function or their volume
Textual Defination: A whole-body PBPK model contains an explicit representation of the organs that are most relevant to the absorption, distribution, excretion, and metabolization of the drug/chemicals due to their physiological/pharmacological function or their volume

Label: Perfusion Limited Model
Defination: Perfusion-limited models are a type of physiologically based pharmacokinetic (PBPK) model that assumes that the concentration of a substance in tissues reaches equilibrium with the substance in the circulation rapidly. In perfusion-limited models, the rate of drug uptake by tissues is limited by blood flow, and the rate of drug elimination is limited by the rate of diffusion from the tissue to the blood
Textual Defination: Perfusion-limited models are a type of physiologically based pharmacokinetic (PBPK) model that assumes that the concentration of a substance in tissues reaches equilibrium with the substance in the circulation rapidly. In perfusion-limited models, the rate of drug uptake by tissues is limited by blood flow, and the rate of drug elimination is limited by the rate of diffusion from the tissue to the blood

Label: Physiological Parameters
Defination: Physiological parameters in PBPK modeling provide the structural framework of the model and are used to simulate the absorption, distribution, metabolism, and excretion (ADME) of a substance throughout the body. These parameters include body weight, height, organ volume, cardiac output, organ blood flow, and tissue composition.
Textual Defination: Physiological parameters in PBPK modeling provide the structural framework of the model and are used to simulate the absorption, distribution, metabolism, and excretion (ADME) of a substance throughout the body. These parameters include body weight, height, organ volume, cardiac output, organ blood flow, and tissue composition.

Label: Body Mass Index
Synonyms/ Denoation:
Body Mass Index
Quetelet Index
body mass index
BMI
Defination:
A general indicator of the body fat an individual is carrying based upon the ratio of weight to height.
A measure that relates body weight to height. BMI is sometimes used to measure total body fat and whether a person is a healthy weight.
Textual Defination: An individual's weight in kilograms divided by the square of the height in meters.

Label: Race
Synonyms/ Denoation:
RACE
Racial Group
Patient Reported Race
Defination: An arbitrary classification of a taxonomic group that is a division of a species. It usually arises as a consequence of geographical isolation within a species and is characterized by shared heredity, physical attributes and behavior, and in the case of humans, by common history, nationality, or geographic distribution.
Textual Defination: A geographic ancestral origin category  assigned to a population group .

Label: Physicochemical Parameters
Defination: Physicochemical parameters of a compound include molecular weight (MW), lipophilicity, solubility, and pKa values, which can usually be determined in vitro. The physicochemical properties of a compound are used to parameterize the PBPK model
Textual Defination: Physicochemical parameters of a compound include molecular weight (MW), lipophilicity, solubility, and pKa values, which can usually be determined in vitro. The physicochemical properties of a compound are used to parameterize the PBPK model

Label: Molecular weight
Defination: The sum of the weight of all the atoms in a molecule.
Textual Defination: Sum of weight of all the atoms in a molecule.

Label: Lipophillicity
Defination: Lipophilicity defined as the affinity or tendency of a substance to dissolve in lipids or hydrophobic environments.
Textual Defination:
Affinity of a molecule or a moiety
for a lipophilic environment

Label: Distribution coefficients
Defination: LogD is the ratio of equilibrium concentration of compound in an organic phase to total concentation of un-ionized and ionized species in the aqueous phase at a given pH.
Textual Defination: LogD distribution constant, better descriptor of lipophilicity of a molecule.

Label: Log P
Defination: LogP is defined as the partition coefficient of a molecule between aqueous and lipophilic phases usually considered as octanol and water.
Textual Defination: Ratio of a dissolved xenoboitic substance in a two-phase system.

Label: Log S
Defination: LogS is directly related to the water solubility of a Xenobiotic defined as a common solubility unit corresponding to the 10-based logarithm of the solubility of a molecule measured in mol/L.
Textual Defination:
Xenoboitic Solubility unit corresponding to  10-based logarithm measured in mol/L. or
log (solubility measured in mol/l).

Label: pka (strongest acidic)
Defination: The pKa is the negative base-10 logarithm of the acid dissociation constant (Ka) of a solution. The lower the pKa, the stronger the acid.
Textual Defination: Negative base-10 logarithm of acid dissociation constant (Ka) of a solution

Label: pkb (strongest basic)
Abbreviation: pKb pK(b) pK(B) affinity constant, Base dissociation constan
Defination:
The strength of a base is determined by using pKb.
The pKb is the negative base-10 logarithm of the base dissociation constant (Kb) of a solution. The lower the pKb, the stronger the base.
Textual Defination: Negative base-10 logarithm of base dissociation constant (Ka) of a solution

Label: Hydrogen acceptor count
Defination: A descriptor that reflects the integer number of hydrogen bond acceptors in a given molecular entity, as determined by a given method. In highly simplified terms, this is usually the count of all negatively or partially negatively charged heteroatoms (e.g. alcohol oxygen) capable of accepting a hydrogen bond.
Textual Defination: A descriptor reflects  integer number of hydrogen bond acceptors in a given molecular entity.

Label: Hydrogen donor count
Defination: A molecular entity that can undergo oxidation by the loss of hydrogen atom(s).
Textual Defination: A molecule can undergo oxidation by  loss of hydrogen.

Label: rotable bond count
Defination: A descriptor that specifies the integer count of bonds in a given molecular entity
Textual Defination: An integer count of bonds in a given molecular entity

Defination: Gastric emptying in PBPK refers to the rate at which the stomach empties its contents into the small intestine. It is an important parameter in PBPK modeling as it can affect the absorption of drugs and xenobiotics.
Textual Defination: Gastric emptying in PBPK refers to the rate at which the stomach empties its contents into the small intestine. It is an important parameter in PBPK modeling as it can affect the absorption of drugs and xenobiotics.

Label: Enterohepatic recirculation

Textual Defination: Recycling through liver by excretion in bile, reabsorption from intestines into portal circulation, passage back into liver, and re-excretion in bile

Label: Specific Intestinal Permeability
Defination: Specific intestinal permeability in PBPK refers to the surface area-normalized transcellular permeability of the intestinal wall for a specific drug or xenobiotic. It is an important parameter in PBPK modeling as it can affect the absorption of drugs and xenobiotics in the intestine
Textual Defination: Specific intestinal permeability in PBPK refers to the surface area-normalized transcellular permeability of the intestinal wall for a specific drug or xenobiotic. It is an important parameter in PBPK modeling as it can affect the absorption of drugs and xenobiotics in the intestine

Defination: The substrate concentration at which the reaction rate is 50% of the Vmax in intestine. Km is a measure of the affinity an enzyme has for its substrate, as the lower the value of Km, the more efficient the enzyme is at carrying out its function at a lower substrate concentration.
Textual Defination: Substrate concentration at which reaction rate is 50% of Vmax in intestine

It affects the distribution and elimination of the drug/chemical in the body. The dissociation constant (KD) is defined as the ratio of the rate constants for the forward and reverse reactions of the drug/chemical-receptor complex.

Label: AUC0-infinity
Defination: the area under the concentration-time curve from dosing (time 0) to infinity, which means the total drug/chemical exposure across time
Textual Defination: the area under the concentration-time curve from dosing (time 0) to infinity, which means the total drug/chemical exposure across time
Definition Source: Shargel, Leon, et al. Applied Biopharmaceutics & Pharmacokinetics. 7th ed., McGraw-Hill Education, 2015, Chaper-4, page number-79.

Label: Area under moment curve
Defination: AUMC is a pharmacokinetic parameter that is calculated by measuring the concentration of a drug/chemical in blood plasma as a function of time and then taking the definite integral of the product of time and concentration squared
Textual Defination: AUMC is a pharmacokinetic parameter that is calculated by measuring the concentration of a drug/chemical in blood plasma as a function of time and then taking the definite integral of the product of time and concentration squared

Label: Mean residence time
Defination: Average time a drug/chemical molecule resides in the body
Textual Defination: Average time a drug/chemical molecule resides in the body
Definition Source: Mean Residence Time (MRT): Understanding How Long Drug Molecules Stay in the Body | Certara

Label: half-life
Defination: the time it takes for the concentration of a drug/chemical in the body to decrease by half
Textual Defination: the time it takes for the concentration of a drug/chemical in the body to decrease by half

Label: bioavailavility
Defination: Bioavailability is defined as the rate and extent to which the active ingredient or active moiety is absorbed from a Xenoboitic product and becomes available at the site of action (US-FDA, CDER, 2014a).
Textual Defination: Bioavailability is defined as the rate and extent to which the active ingredient or active moiety is absorbed from a Xenoboitic product and becomes available at the site of action (US-FDA, CDER, 2014a).
Definition Source:
Shargel, Leon, et al. Applied Biopharmaceutics & Pharmacokinetics. 7th ed., McGraw-Hill Education, 2015.
Chapter 16, Page Number-471

Label: Relative bioavailability
Defination: Relative bioavailability is a term used to describe the extent and rate at which a drug/chemical is absorbed into the systemic circulation after administration compared to a reference formulation/source chemical,
Textual Defination: Relative bioavailability is a term used to describe the extent and rate at which a drug/chemical is absorbed into the systemic circulation after administration compared to a reference formulation/source chemical,
Definition Source:
Shargel, Leon, et al. Applied Biopharmaceutics & Pharmacokinetics. 7th ed., McGraw-Hill Education, 2015.
Chapter 16, Page Number-473

Label: Mean absorption time
Defination: Average time it takes for drug/chemical to be absorbed into systemic circulation
Textual Defination: Average time it takes for drug/chemical to be absorbed into systemic circulation
Definition Source: Shargel, Leon, et al. Applied Biopharmaceutics & Pharmacokinetics. 7th ed., McGraw-Hill Education, 2015.Chapter-25,Page number-837

Label: Mean dissolution time
Defination: Average time it takes for drug/chemical to dissolve in body
Textual Defination: Average time it takes for drug/chemical to dissolve in body
Definition Source:
Shargel, Leon, et al. Applied Biopharmaceutics & Pharmacokinetics. 7th ed., McGraw-Hill Education, 2015.
Chapter-25,Page number-837

Label: Bioequivalence
Defination: Bioequivalence is defined as the absence of a significant difference in the rate and extent to which the chemical ingredient or moiety becomes available at the site of action when administered at the same molar dose under similar conditions.
Textual Defination: Identical comparison between test (T) and reference (R) xenoboitic product
Definition Source: Shargel, Leon, et al. Applied Biopharmaceutics & Pharmacokinetics. 7th ed., McGraw-Hill Education, 2015.Chapter 16, Page Number-471

Label: absolute bioavailability
Defination: Fraction of treatment dose that reaches systemic circulation and ratio of xenobiotics amount in system after administration of a test xenobiotics to xenobiotics in system after IV administration
Textual Defination: Fraction of treatment dose that reaches systemic circulation and ratio of xenobiotics amount in system after administration of a test xenobiotics to xenobiotics in system after IV administration

Label: elimination phase
Defination: The elimination phase is a phase in PBPK that describes the process of removing an administered drug/chemical from the body

Label: absorption phase
Defination: Phase describing how drug/chemical goes in systemic circulation from site of administration
Textual Defination: Phase describing how drug/chemical goes in systemic circulation from site of administration
Definition Source: Drug Absorption - Clinical Pharmacology - Merck Manuals Professional Edition

Label: CL/F
Defination: describes the rate at which a drug/chemical is eliminated from the body after oral administration
Textual Defination: describes the rate at which a drug/chemical is eliminated from the body after oral administration

Label: Aurine
Defination: Amount of substance present in urine
Textual Defination: Amount of substance present in urine

Label: Afeces
Defination: Amount of substance present in feces
Textual Defination: Amount of substance present in feces

Label: Cumulative amount in urine
Defination: total amount of drug/chemical or metabolite excreted in urine over specific period of time
Textual Defination: total amount of drug/chemical or metabolite excreted in urine over specific period of time
Definition Source: Chapter 19. Cumulative Urinary Excretion | Handbook of Basic Pharmacokinetics  Including Clinical Applications, 7th Edition | PharmacyLibrary

Label: Cumulative amount in feces
Defination: total amount of drug/chemical or metabolite excreted in feces over specific period of time
Textual Defination: total amount of drug/chemical or metabolite excreted in feces over specific period of time

Label: Creatinine
Defination: The breakdown product of creatine, a constituent of muscle tissue, that is excreted by the kidney and whose serum level is used to evaluate kidney function.
Textual Defination: breakdown product of creatine which excreted in urine

Label: AUCss
Defination: Steady state area under curve

Label: Plasma concentration
Textual Defination: Xenobiotic concentration in plasma, derived from full blood

Label: Min Organ Concentration
Defination: Minimum organ concentration

Label: Max organ concentration
Defination: Maximum organ concentration

Label: Median Organ concentration
Defination: Medium organ concentration

Label: Percentile 2.5 plasma concentration
Defination: Percentile 2.5 plasma concentration

Label: percetile 97.5 plasma concentration
Defination: percetile 97.5 plasma concentration

Label: Tolerable daily intake
Defination: estimate of the amount of a substance in air, food or drinking water that can be taken in daily over a lifetime without appreciable health risk
Textual Defination: estimate of the amount of a substance in air, food or drinking water that can be taken in daily over a lifetime without appreciable health risk

Label: Reconstructed exposure
Defination: Method used to estimate the eamount of a substance a person has been exposed by using internal body measurements

Label: Estimated daily intake
Defination: measure used to estimate the amount of a substance that a person consumes daily through food or other sources
Textual Defination: measure used to estimate the amount of a substance that a person consumes daily through food or other sources
Definition Source: Guidance for Industry: Estimating Dietary Intake of Substances in Food | FDA

Label: Biomonitoring equivalent
Defination: The concentration of a chemical (or metabolite) in a biological medium (blood, urine, human milk, etc.) consistent with defined exposure guidance values or toxicity criteria including reference doses and reference concentrations (RfD and RfCs), minimal risk levels (MRLs), or tolerable daily intakes (TDIs)
Textual Defination: chemical concentration (or metabolite) in biological medium (eg. blood, urine, human milk) consistent with defined exposure guidance values or toxicity criteria including reference doses and reference concentrations, minimal risk levels or tolerable daily intakes
Definition Source: Hays S. M., et al. Guidelines for the derivation of biomonitoring equivalents: Report from the biomonitoring equivalents expert workshop. Regulatory Toxicology and Pharmacology V51(3), 2008, Pages S4-S15. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.yrtph.2008.05.004

Label: HBM-HBGV
Defination: Human Biomonitoring Health-Based Guidance Value. It is a measure used to establish safe levels of a substance in blood or urine based on human biomonitoring data
Textual Defination: Human Biomonitoring Health-Based Guidance Value. It is a measure used to establish safe levels of a substance in blood or urine based on human biomonitoring data

Label: Reference dose
Defination: Estimate (with uncertainty spanning perhaps an order of magnitude) of a daily oral or dermal exposure to the human population (including sensitive subgroups) that is likely to be without an appreciable risk of deleterious effects during a lifetime. Its unit is usually mg/kg bw/day or mg/kg.
Textual Defination: Daily oral or dermal exposure estimation to human population (including sensitive subgroups)

Label: Acceptable daily intake
Defination: An estimate of the amount of a substance in food or drinking water that can be consumed daily over a lifetime without presenting an appreciable risk to health. It is usually expressed as milligrams of the substance per kilogram of body weight and applies to chemical substances such as food additives, pesticide residues and veterinary Xenoboitics
Textual Defination: Substance in food or drinking water that consumed daily over a lifetime without presenting appreciable risk to health

Label: Human biomonitoring
Defination: An instrument for measuring the internal dose of exogenous substances/chemicals that enter a body during a certain period of exposure from a range of sources
Textual Defination: Measuring instrument for internal dose of exogenous substances/chemicals that enter a body during a certain exposure period from different sources
Definition Source: World Health Organization. Regional Office for Europe. (?2023)?. Human biomonitoring. Basics: educational course. World Health Organization. Regional Office for Europe. https://apps.who.int/iris/handle/10665/368163. License: CC BY-NC-SA 3.0 IGO

Label: Reverse dosimetry
Defination: An estimation of environmental exposures consistent with measured biological monitoring data
Textual Defination: Environmental exposures estimation, consistent with measured biological monitoring data
Definition Source: Ruiz, P., & Fowler, B. A. (2015). Exposure Assessment, Forward and Reverse Dosimetry. Handbook on the Toxicology of Metals, 141 153. doi:10.1016/b978-0-444-59453-2.00007-X

Label: Forward dosimetry
Defination: an estimation of internal exposures from measurements of external exposure in studies characterizing chemical toxicity
Textual Defination: Estimation from external exposure mesurements in studies characterizing chemical toxicity
Definition Source: Ruiz, P., & Fowler, B. A. (2015). Exposure Assessment, Forward and Reverse Dosimetry. Handbook on the Toxicology of Metals, 141 153. doi:10.1016/b978-0-444-59453-2.00007-X

Label: Spot urine
Defination: single, untimed urine specimen, voided spontaneously by the patient. The sample is analyzed to determine its protein, creatinine, or electrolyte content. This type of specimen differs from a timed urinary specimen, which represents all the urine a patient produces over a 12- or 24-hr period.
Textual Defination: Single, untimed urine specimen, voided spontaneously by patient and is used to determine its protein, creatinine, or electrolyte content

Label: Specific gravity
Defination: The ratio of the density of a material to the density of some standard material, such as water or air, at a specified temperature.
Textual Defination: Ratio of material density to some standard material density like water or air at specified temperature

Label: Biological matrix
Defination: A biological matrix is a biological material, such as blood, urine, or tissue, that is used for analysis in scientific research and medical testing
Textual Defination: A biological matrix is a biological material, such as blood, urine, or tissue, that is used for analysis in scientific research and medical testing

Label: Hair
Defination: filament-like structure composed of keratin, consisting of a shaft which projects to the surface of the skin from a root which is softer than the shaft and lodges in the cavity of a hair follicle.
Textual Defination: Keratin composed filament-like structure, consisting of shaft, projecting to skin surface from root which is softer than shaft and lodges in hair follicle cavity

Label: Nail
Defination:
A horn-like keratin structure covering the dorsal aspect of the terminal phalanges of fingers and toes.
The cutaneous plate on the dorsal surface of the distal end of a finger or toe.
Textual Defination: Cutaneous plate on dorsal surface of distal end of finger or toe

Label: Teeth
Defination: One of a set of bone-like structures in the mouth used for biting and chewing
Textual Defination: Set of bone-like structures in mouth used for biting and chewing

Label: Blood
Defination: A liquid tissue; its major function is to transport oxygen throughout the body. It also supplies the tissues with nutrients, removes waste products, and contains various components of the immune system defending the body against infection. Several hormones also travel in the blood.
Textual Defination: Liquid tissue which transport oxygen, nutrients, removes waste products, and contains various components of immune system defending body against infection

Label: Urine
Defination:
The fluid produced by the kidneys.
Fluid containing water and waste products. Urine is made by the kidneys, stored in the bladder, and leaves the body through the urethra.
Textual Defination: Fluid, excreted by the kidneys and is stored in bladder and discharged through urethra

Label: Permeability limited PBPK
Defination: permeability-limited PBPK models consider the permeability of the substance into and out of capillaries, cell membranes, and intracellular lipids. the rate of diffusion across tissue membrane is the limiting factor

Label: Vmax_baso_in vitro
Defination: Vmax of basolateral transporter

Label: km_baso
Defination: km of basolateral transporter

Label: Vmax_apical_invitro
Defination: Vmax of apical transporter

Label: km_apical
Defination: km of apical transporter

Label: RAFapi
Defination: Apical transporter

Label: RAFbaso
Defination: Basolateral transporters

Label: Kiff
Defination: describe the influx pathway of a chemical, which is the process by which a chemical moves from the extracellular fluid or plasma into a cell

Label: KeffluxC
Defination: describe the efflux pathway of a chemical, which is the process by which a chemical moves from inside a cell to the extracellular fluid or plasma

Label: Endosomal Space
Defination: endosomal space is a compartment within the endosomal-lysosomal system, which is a set of intracellular membranous compartments that dynamically interconvert

Label: Interstitial Space
Defination: the fluid-filled space that lies between blood vessels and cells, providing the fluid and structural environment surrounding those cells

Label: effective permeability (Peff)
Defination: Effective permeability is a measure of the rate at which a substance can pass through a barrier, such as a cell membrane or capillary walls
Textual Defination: Effective permeability is a measure of the rate at which a substance can pass through a barrier, such as a cell membrane or capillary wal

Label: Population PBPK
Defination: It is considered for the identification of interindividual variability in a population and the characterization of its physiological and ADME (absorption, distribution, metabolization, excretion)-related sources.
Textual Defination: model used for interindividual variability identification in population, its physiological characterization and ADME related sources
Definition Source: Krauss M., et al. Bayesian Population Physiologically-Based Pharmacokinetic (PBPK) Approach for a Physiologically Realistic Characterization of Interindividual Variability in Clinically Relevant Populations. PLoS ONE 2015. 10(10): e0139423. https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0139423

Label: top-down PBPK
Defination: Modelling and simulation approach based on the observed clinical data, mainly empirical with the scope of utilization narrowed down to the range of the input data
Textual Defination: Modelling and simulation approach based on observed clinical data, empirical with utilization scope, narrowed down to input data range
Definition Source: Tylutki, Z. et al. Top-down, Bottom-up and Middle-out Strategies for Xenoboitic Cardiac Safety Assessment via Modeling and Simulations. Curr Pharmacol Rep 2, 171 177 (2016). https://doi.org/10.1007/s40495-016-0060-3

Label: bottom-up pbpk
Defination: Modelling and simulation approach based on knowledge about the human body, therefore, as mechanistic as possible, utilizing in vitro information as the input data
Textual Defination: Modelling and simulation approach based on knowledge of human body, therefore, as mechanistic as possible, utilizing in vitro information as input data
Definition Source: Tylutki, Z. et al. Top-down, Bottom-up and Middle-out Strategies for Xenoboitic Cardiac Safety Assessment via Modeling and Simulations. Curr Pharmacol Rep 2, 171 177 (2016). https://doi.org/10.1007/s40495-016-0060-3

Label: one-compartment PBPK
Defination: A one-compartment model assumes that all the tissues in the body are contained in a single compartment called the  central compartment.

Label: central compartment
Defination: component of a two compartment pharmacokinetic model representing plasma and highly perfused organs
Textual Defination: component of a two compartment pharmacokinetic model representing plasma and highly perfused organs

Label: Peripheral Compartment
Defination: component of a two compartment pharmacokinetic model representing less perfused organ like muscle and fat.
Textual Defination: It consists of tissues where Xenoboitic distribution is slower
Definition Source: Two Compartment Body Model and Vd Terms (ufl.edu)

Label: linear elimination
Defination: elimination following first-order kinetics.

Label: non-linear elimination
Defination: a pharmacokinetic (PK) phenomenon where the elimination of a drug from the body does not follow first-order kinetics
Definition Source: Goodness of fit for nonlinear model - Cross Validated (stackexchange.com)

Label: goodness of fit
Defination: a model evaluation technique used to assess how well a statistical model fits the observed data

Label: Observed
Defination: exprimental data

Label: Predicted
Defination: predicted by the model

Label: visual predictive check
Defination: provides a visual comparison between observed data and model predictions

Label: average fold error
Defination: a metric used to assess the accuracy of predictions made by a model. It is calculated as the average of the absolute values of the differences between the predicted and observed values, divided by the observed values

Label: Residual error magnitude
Defination: the magnitude of the difference between the observed value and the predicted value in a regression analysis.
Definition Source: Residual Standard Deviation/Error: Guide for Beginners   QUANTIFYING HEALTH

Label: Mean Relative derivation
Defination: a measure of the deviation of a set of values from their mean, expressed as a percentage
Textual Defination: a measure of the deviation of a set of values from their mean, expressed as a percentage
Definition Source: How to Find a Relative Average Deviation | Sciencing

Label: Geometric mean fold error
Defination: a measure used to compare predicted and observed values in pharmacokinetic models
Textual Defination: a measure used to compare predicted and observed values in pharmacokinetic models

Label: Sensitivty Analysis
Defination: The process of investigating the role of input parameters in determining the model output. It seeks to quantify the importance of each model input parameter on the output.
Textual Defination: Quantifying process of investigating input parameters role in determining model output

Label: Local Senstivity analysis
Defination: analyzes the effect of one model parameter at a time, keeping the other parameters fixed
Textual Defination: analyzes the effect of one model parameter at a time, keeping the other parameters fixed
Definition Source: Sensitivity Analysis in SimBiology - MATLAB & Simulink (mathworks.com)

Label: Global Sensitvity analysis
Defination: quantifies the impact of variations in model inputs on the model output. A sensitivity analysis is considered to be global when all the input factors are varied simultaneously and the sensitivity is evaluated over the entire range of each input factor.
Textual Defination: quantifies the impact of variations in model inputs on the model output. A sensitivity analysis is considered to be global when all the input factors are varied simultaneously and the sensitivity is evaluated over the entire range of each input factor.

Label: one at a time sensitivity analysis
Defination: It analyzes the effect of one parameter on the cost function at a time, keeping the other parameters fixed. They explore only a small fraction of the design space, especially when there are many parameters. Also, they do not provide insight about how the interactions between parameters influence the cost function.
Textual Defination: It analyzes effect of one parameter on cost function at a time, keeping other parameters fixed. eg. Local sensitivity analysis

Label: Lifetsages
Defination: Life stages in the context of the human species refer to the different phases of an individual's life, from birth to death.
Textual Defination: Life stages in the context of the human species refer to the different phases of an individual's life, from birth to death.

Label: Fetus
Defination: A fetus is the growth  and developmental stage of a mammal,  after the embryonic stage.
Textual Defination: Unborn offspring in uterus representing  postembryonic stage of development until birth.

Label: Infants
Defination: An infant is a very young child,  under the age of one year, who is in the early stages of life and development, especially in the period immediately following birth.
Textual Defination: An infant is a very young child, under age of one year.

Label: Toddlers
Defination: Toddlers are young children who are  between the ages of one and three years old.  (infancy to early childhood)
Textual Defination: Young children who are  between  ages of one and three years old.  (infancy to early childhood)

Label: Children
Defination: Children are young human beings  ranging from 3-11 years.
Textual Defination: Children, who are in  early ages ranging from 3-11 years.

Label: Teenagers
Defination: A human life stage that begins at eleven years of age and continues until fifteen years of age.
Textual Defination: A human life stage that begins at eleven years of age and continues until fifteen years of age.

Label: Adolescent
Defination: An adolescent is a young person who is in the transitional stage between Teenagers and adulthood.(Age range of 15 till 18 years)
Textual Defination: An adolescent, transitional stage between Teenagers and adulthood.(Age range of 15 till 18 years)

Label: Adult
Defination: A human life stage that begins at eighteen years of age and continues until thirty years of age.
Textual Defination: A human life stage that begins at eighteen years of age and continues until thirty years of age.

Label: Middle age
Defination: A human life stage that begins at thirty years of age and continues until forty-five years of age.
Textual Defination: A human life stage that begins at thirty years of age and continues until forty-five years of age.

Label: old age
Defination: A human life stage that begins at forty-five years of age and continues until sixty years of age.
Textual Defination: A human life stage that begins at forty-five years of age and continues until sixty years of age.

Label: pediatric
Defination: A human population, below fifteen years of age
Textual Defination: A human population, below fifteen years of age

Label: geriatric
Defination: Geriatric refers to the medical specialty focused on providing care for the unique health needs of older adults
Textual Defination: Geriatric refers to the medical specialty focused on providing care for the unique health needs of older adults

Label: Normal child
Defination: A normal child, has no serious physical or mental health problems.
Textual Defination: A normal child, has no serious physical or mental health problems.

Label: obese child
Defination: A Body Mass Index (BMI) greater than or equal to the 95th percentile for age and gender in children aged two years and older.
Textual Defination: A Body Mass Index (BMI) greater than or equal to the 95th percentile for age and gender in children aged two years and older.

Label: Uncertainty
Defination: Uncertainty in Physiologically Based Pharmacokinetic (PBPK) modeling is introduced by two main sources: the underlying biology or mechanisms, and drug/chemical-related parameters
Textual Defination: Uncertainty in Physiologically Based Pharmacokinetic (PBPK) modeling is introduced by two main sources: the underlying biology or mechanisms, and drug/chemical-related parameters

Label: Variability
Defination: Inter-individual differences  in the anatomical and physiological characteristics of humans or animal
Textual Defination: Inter-individual differences  in anatomical and physiological characteristics

Label: Monte carlo simulation
Defination: Monte Carlo simulation is a form of uncertainty analysis that allows the propagation of uncertainty through a model, which results in an estimate of the variance in model output
Textual Defination: Monte Carlo simulation is a form of uncertainty analysis that allows the propagation of uncertainty through a model, which results in an estimate of the variance in model output

Label: Brain PBPK
Defination: Brain PBPK model build to predict the concentration of drug/chemical in different brain regions with respect to time

Label: Spinal CSF volume
Defination: total volume of CSF present in spine

Label: Cranial CSF volume
Defination: total volume of CSF present in cranial

Label: Brain mass
Defination: brain weight measured in Kg or pounds

Label: BBB
Defination: Blood-brain-barrier

Label: Spinal CSF flow
Defination: total CSF flowing in spinal region

Label: Cranial CSF flow
Defination: total CSF flowing in cranial region

Label: BCSFB
Defination: Blood-cerebrospinal fluid- barrier

Label: vhippocampus
Defination: volume of hippocampus

Label: vfrontalcortex
Defination: volume of frontal cortex

Label: vcerebrum
Defination: volume of cerebrum

Label: vcerebellum
Defination: volume of cerebellum

Label: Qhippocampus
Defination: Qhippocampus is a parameter used in PBPK modeling to describe the blood flow rate to thehippocampus, which is used to calculate the rate of drug/chemical delivery to the hippocampus. The value of Qhippocampus depends on the species of interest and is defined by the hippocampus weight/volume and cardiac output

Label: Qfrontalcortex
Defination: Qfrontalcortex is a parameter used in PBPK modeling to describe the blood flow rate to the frontalcortex, which is used to calculate the rate of drug/chemical delivery to the frontalcortex. The value of Qfrontalcortex depends on the species of interest and is defined by the frontalcortex weight/volume and cardiac output

Label: Qcerebrum
Defination: Qcerebrum is a parameter used in PBPK modeling to describe the blood flow rate to the cerebrum, which is used to calculate the rate of drug/chemical delivery to the cerebrum. The value of Qcerebrum depends on the species of interest and is defined by the cerebrum weight/volume and cardiac output

Label: Qcerebellum
Defination: Qcerebellum is a parameter used in PBPK modeling to describe the blood flow rate to the cerebellum, which is used to calculate the rate of drug/chemical delivery to the cerebellum. The value of Qcerebellum depends on the species of interest and is defined by the cerebellum weight/volume and cardiac output

Label: Khippocampus:brain
Defination: ratio of drug/chemical concentration in the hippocampus tissue to its concentration in the plasma

Label: kcerebrum:brain
Defination: ratio of drug/chemical concentration in the cerebrum tissue to its concentration in the plasma

Label: kcerebellum:brain
Defination: ratio of drug/chemical concentration in the cerebellum tissue to its concentration in the plasma

Label: kfrontalcortex:brain
Defination: ratio of drug/chemical concentration in the frontal cortex tissue to its concentration in the plasma

Label: Pappcerebrum:brain
Defination: Permeability of drug/chemical in cerebrum to brain

Label: Pappcerebellum:brain
Defination: Permeability of drug/chemical in cerebellum to brain

Label: Papphippocampus:brain
Defination: Permeability of drug/chemical in hippocampus to brain

Label: Pappcortex:brain
Defination: Permeability of drug/chemical in cortex to brain

Label: Pregnant PBPK
Defination: PBPK model build to predict the concentration of drug/chemical in pregnant female with time

Label: fetoplacental volume
Defination: Volume can be calculated by adding the uterus weight, placenta volume, fetal volume, and amniotic fluid volume

Label: vfetus
Defination: Volume of fetus

Label: vplacenta
Defination: Volume of placenta

Label: vamnioticfluid
Defination: Volume of amniotic fluid

Label: vliverfetus
Defination: Volume of liver in fetus

Label: vbrainfetus
Defination: Volume of brain in fetus

Label: vkidneyfetus
Defination: Volume of kidney in fetus

Label: vrestbodyfetus
Defination: Volume of rest body in fetus calculated by subtracting the body with all the organs mentioned in PBPK

Label: placenta volume
Defination: volume of placenta

Label: fetal cardiac output
Defination: Fetal Cardiac output in PBPK modeling refers to the volume of blood pumped by the fetal heart per unit of time, which is used to calculate the rate of blood flow to different organs and tissues in the fetal body

Label: Qliverfetus
Defination: Qliverfetus is a parameter used in PBPK modeling to describe the blood flow rate to the liver fetus, which is used to calculate the rate of drug/chemical delivery to the liver in fetus. The value of Qliverfetus depends on the species of interest and is defined by the fetal liver weight/volume and cardiac output

Label: Qkidneyfetus
Defination: Qkidneyfetus is a parameter used in PBPK modeling to describe the blood flow rate to the kidney fetus, which is used to calculate the rate of drug/chemical delivery to the kidney in fetus. The value of Qkidneyfetus depends on the species of interest and is defined by the fetal kidney weight/volume and cardiac output

Label: Qbrainfetus
Defination: Qbrainfetus is a parameter used in PBPK modeling to describe the blood flow rate to the brain fetus, which is used to calculate the rate of drug/chemical delivery to the brain in fetus. The value of Qbrainfetus depends on the species of interest and is defined by the fetal brain weight/volume and cardiac output

Label: Qrestbodyfetus
Defination: Qrestbodyfetus is a parameter used in PBPK modeling to describe the blood flow rate to the restbody fetus, which is used to calculate the rate of drug/chemical delivery to the restbody in fetus. The value of Qrestbodyfetus depends on the species of interest and is calculating by sutracting the total blood flow by the all organ considered in fetal pbpk

Label: Gestational age
Defination: measure of the age of a pregnancy, indicating how far along the pregnancy is. Typically measured in weeks

Label: Gestational week
Defination: measure of the week of a pregnancy, indicating how far along the pregnancy is.

Label: Vmax fetus
Defination: Vmax for a particular drug/chemical in fetus

Label: aminotic transfer coefficient
Defination: Rate at which drug/chemical transfer from materal circulation to amniotic fluid

Label: Kliverfetus:plasma
Defination: ratio of compound concentration in the fetus of liver tissue to its concentration in the plasma

Label: kbrainfetus:plasma
Defination: ratio of compound concentration in the fetus of brain tissue to its concentration in the plasma

Label: kkidneyfetus:plasma
Defination: ratio of compound concentration in the fetus of kidney tissue to its concentration in the plasma

Label: krestbodyfetus:plasma
Defination: ratio of compound concentration in the fetus of restbody tissue to its concentration in the plasma

Label: Kidney PBPK
Defination: Kidney PBPK model is build to predict the concentration of compound in different compartments of kidney with time

Label: Bowmans capsule
Defination: A double-walled epithelial capsule that is the bulbous closed proximal end of the kidney tubular system. It surrounds the cluster of convoluted capillaries of KIDNEY GLOMERULUS and is continuous with the convoluted PROXIMAL KIDNEY TUBULE.
Textual Defination: Double-walled epithelial capsule that is bulbous closed proximal end of kidney tubular system

Label: Filtrate
Defination: Filtrate is a role of liquid outcome of a filtration process that is commonly the mechanical or physical operation which is used for the separation of solids from fluids (liquids or gases) by interposing a medium through which only the fluid can pass
Textual Defination: Role of liquid outcome of filtration process, commonly mechanical or physical operation which is used for solids separation from fluids (liquids or gases) by interposing medium through which only fluid can pass

Label: Proximal tubule
Defination: The proximal segment of the pronephric tubule, closest to the glomus and functioning in solute resorption and waste excretion
Textual Defination: Proximal segment of pronephric tubule, closest to glomus and functioning in solute resorption and waste excretion

Label: loop of henle
Defination: A highly specialized segment of the mammalian kidney tubules, that dips into the medulla
Textual Defination: Highly specialized segment of mammalian kidney tubules that dips into medulla

Label: distal tubule
Defination: The distal segment of the pronephric tubule, functioning in water resorption, with urine passing through it into the pronephric duct.
Textual Defination: Distal segment of pronephric tubule, functioning in water resorption, with urine passing through it into pronephric duct

Label: bladder
Defination: The distensible sac-like organ that functions as a reservoir of urine, collecting from the kidneys and eliminating via the urethra.
Textual Defination: Distensible sac-like organ, functioning as urine reservoir, collecting from kidneys and eliminating via urethra

Label: lung PBPK
Defination: PBPK model built to predict the compound concnetration in lung compartment

Label: extrathoracic
Defination: the area outside of the thorax, which includes the head, neck, and upper respiratory tract. In the context of PBPK modeling, extrathoracic deposition refers to the amount of inhaled drug/chemical that is deposited in the head and upper respiratory tract before reaching the lungs

Label: Gut PBPK or ADAM model
Defination: PBPK model build to predict the concentration of drug/chemical in different compartments of gut.

Label: FQduodenum
Defination: Fraction of blood flow to duodenum

Label: FQjejunum
Defination: Fraction of blood flow to jejunum

Label: FQileum
Defination: Fraction of blood flow to ileum

Label: FQcolon
Defination: Fraction of blood flow to colon

Label: FQcecum
Defination: Fraction of blood flow to cecum

Label: Qduodenum
Defination: Qduodenum is a parameter used in PBPK modeling to describe the blood flow rate to the duodenum, which is used to calculate the rate of drug/chemical delivery to the duodenum. The value of Qduodenum depends on the species of interest and is defined by the duodenum weight/volume and cardiac output

Label: Qjejunum
Defination: Qjejunum is a parameter used in PBPK modeling to describe the blood flow rate to the jejunum, which is used to calculate the rate of drug/chemical delivery to the jejunum. The value of Qjejunum depends on the species of interest and is defined by the jejunum weight/volume and cardiac output

Label: Qileum
Defination: Qileum is a parameter used in PBPK modeling to describe the blood flow rate to the duodenum, which is used to calculate the rate of drug/chemical delivery to the ileum. The value of Qileum depends on the species of interest and is defined by the ileum weight/volume and cardiac output

Label: Qcolon
Defination: Qcolon is a parameter used in PBPK modeling to describe the blood flow rate to the colon, which is used to calculate the rate of drug/chemical delivery to the colon. The value of Qcolon depends on the species of interest and is defined by the colon weight/volume and cardiac output

Label: Qcecum
Defination: Qcecum is a parameter used in PBPK modeling to describe the blood flow rate to the cecum, which is used to calculate the rate of drug/chemical delivery to the cecum. The value of Qcecum depends on the species of interest and is defined by the cecum weight/volume and cardiac output

Label: Fduodenum
Defination: duodenum volume as a fraction of total body weight

Label: Fjejunum
Defination: jejunum volume as a fraction of total body weight

Label: Fileum
Defination: ileum volume as a fraction of total body weight

Label: Fcolon
Defination: colon volume as a fraction of total body weight

Label: Fcecum
Defination: cecum volume as a fraction of total body weight

Label: Vduodenum
Defination: Volume of duodenum

Label: Vjejunum
Defination: Volume of jejunum

Label: Vileum
Defination: Volume of ileum

Label: Vcolon
Defination: Volume of colon

Label: Vcecum
Defination: Volume of cecum

Label: mean precipitation time
Defination: mean precipitation time is often used to predict the behavior of drugs/chemical in the human body, specifically in relation to food effects and the fasted state

Label: diffusion coefficient
Defination: The diffusion coefficient defined as the amount of a xenoboitic that diffuses across a membrane of a given unit area per unit time when the concentration gradient is unity.
Textual Defination: Xenoboitic amount ,i.s diffuses across a membrane of a given unit area per unit time
Definition Source: Shargel, Leon, et al. Applied Biopharmaceutics & Pharmacokinetics. 7th ed., McGraw-Hill Education, 2015. Chaper-14,page number-380

Label: particle density
Defination: a measure of the mass per unit volume of the particle. It is expressed in terms of Mg m-3.
Textual Defination: Measure of mass per unit volume of particle

Label: intestinal transit time
Defination: time required for compound to move through the intestine

Label: Lactational PBPK
Defination: PBPK models built to predict the drug/chemical concentration in milk during lactation

Label: Milk:plasma ratio
Defination: Milk to plasma ratio of a particular chemical

Label: fumilk
Defination: fraction unbound of a chemical in milk

Label: Cmilk
Defination: concentration in milk

Label: daily milk intake
Defination: daily milk ingested by the baby from mother

Label: phmilk
Defination: Ph of milk

Label: Blood-milk-barrier
Defination: physiological barrier that separates the blood and milk compartments in lactating species.

Label: milk:plasma partition
Defination: partition coefficient of chemical from plasma to milk
